<h1>From Robert Carter Nicholas</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Dear Sir.</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Virginia 3d Feby 1776</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>I have to acknowledge the Receipt of your very obliging favr by Capt. Matthews.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0179-fn-0001" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0179-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> Your former Letter in Answer to mine by Mr Byrd I received in due time, &amp; took the earliest Opportunity of recommending it to our Delegates to fix upon some Method to defray the Expences incurrd by this Country in the northern Colonies. This they tell me that they have not been
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-03-02-pb-0243">[243]</span>
able to effect, so that I have been obliged to stretch my own Credit in England to furnish them with Bills of Excha. for their immediate Purposes. I particularly recommended to them to try at reimbursing you what you might be in Advance for Mr Byrd, but I dont beleive they have had it in their power yet.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0179-fn-0002" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0179-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> Indeed I know they have been obliged to borrow Money towards paying for Arms &amp;c. purchased for us at Philadelphia. These Inconveniencies, however, I hope will soon be remedied, as the Congress hath agreed to take part, at least, of our Troops on Continental Pay, wch will enable us to exchange our Money for that of the Continent.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0179-fn-0003" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0179-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> Indeed, considering our Union in other Respects, it has been Matter of Wonder to me, that our Currency should want equal Credit in other Colonies. I shall write to Colo. Harrison about Mr Byrds Affair &amp; desire the favr of you to send him Mr Byrds Account.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0179-fn-0004" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0179-fn-0004-ptr">4</a></p>
<p>I cannot but condole with you on the Loss of Genl Montgomerie &amp; the other brave Officers &amp; Soldiers before Quebeck. This will be Matter of great Triumph to our Enemies, but I hope of not long Continuance.</p>
<p>Our Sentiments on the Situation of this Country &amp; the Measures necessary to be pursued coincide exactly; but we are much puzled how to manage those amphibious Animals we have to deal with.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0179-fn-0005" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0179-fn-0005-ptr">5</a> The different Occurrences here you, no doubt, have pretty regular Accounts of thro the Channel of our News Papers, as the Printers never fail publishing every Incident of the least Importance. You must have heard of the Destruction of the greater part of Norfolk by the Men of War &amp; their infernal Crimes, &amp; I expect that the Remains will soon be laid in Ashes.</p>
<p>I hope your Lady is safe &amp; well with you. I beg my respectful Complts to her, Mr Custis &amp; his Lady. That the Almighty may take you &amp; yr whole Corps under his Protection &amp; crown your Endeavours to preserve the Liberties of America with Success is the ardent Wish of, Dr Sir, Yr affte &amp; mo. obt Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Ro. C. Nicholas</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0179-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0179-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0179-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>Letter not found.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0179-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0179-fn-0002">2</a>
	
   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-01-02-0328" class="document">Nicholas to GW, 8 Sept. 1775</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0102" class="document">GW to Nicholas, 5 Oct. 1775</a>. Nicholas, the treasurer of Virginia, wrote to the colonys delegates in Congress on 25 Nov. 1775 about the need for money and ended his remarks on
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-03-02-pb-0244">[244]</span>
the subject by commenting: How I shall remit young Mr. [Francis Otway] Byrds Allowance, I do not know, and should be obliged by your Advice. The General has kindly promised me that he shall not want; but then he ought to be regularly reimbursed (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Julian P. Boyd et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;The Papers of Thomas Jefferson&lt;/i&gt;. 40 vols. to date. Princeton, N.J., 1950. ]">Boyd, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Jefferson Papers</span></span>, 1:26668; see also Nicholas to Jefferson, 10 Nov. and 12 Dec. 1775, ibid., 25456, 27172). On 1 Feb. 1776 Byrd received 30.10 from GW for his service in the army since 1 Dec. 1775 (vouchers and receipted accounts, 177583, vol. 24, ser. 5, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>). GW did not receive final payment until 1784 for his out-of-pocket expenditure for Byrd in 177576 (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-04-01-02-0025" class="document">James Milligan to GW, 13 Jan. 1784</a>).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0179-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0179-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>Congress adopted six Virginia regiments on 28 Dec. 1775 (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 3:463).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0179-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0179-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>Nicholas wrote to Benjamin Harrison on this date, and on 13 Feb. Harrison replied to Nicholas: I do not remember ever to have seen a Letter of yours on the Subject of geting Mr. Byrd his money; I have forwarded your letter to the General and will take Care when I get his Answer that the money shall be paid (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Paul H. Smith et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Letters of Delegates to Congress, 17741789&lt;/i&gt;. 26 vols. Washington, D.C., 19762000. ]">Smith, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Letters of Delegates</span></span>, 3:24546). No correspondence between Harrison and GW about this matter has been found.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0179-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0179-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>British naval power enabled them to conduct amphibious operations almost anywhere along the American coast or rivers below the fall line.</p>

</div>
</div>
